SIMPLE: hermetical
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hermetical
<hw>Her*met"ic*al</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>herm⟦eacute⟧tique</ets>. See Note under <er>Hermes</er>, 1.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Of, pertaining to, or taught by, Hermes Trismegistus;
<as>as, <ex>hermetic</ex> philosophy</as>. Hence: Alchemical;
chemic.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Delusions of the <xex>hermetic</xex> art.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The alchemists, as the people were called who tried to make gold,
considered themselves followers of Hermes, and often called themselves
<qex>Hermetic</qex> philosophers.</q> <rj><qau>A. B.
Buckley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the system which explains the
causes of diseases and the operations of medicine on the principles of
the hermetic philosophy, and which made much use, as a remedy, of an
alkali and an acid; <as>as, <ex>hermetic</ex> medicine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Made perfectly close or air-tight by fusion, so that
no gas or spirit can enter or escape; <as>as, an <ex>hermetic</ex>
seal</as>. See Note under <er>Hermetically</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hermetic art</b></col>, <cd>alchemy.</cd> --
<col><b>Hermetic books</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Books of the
Egyptians, which treat of astrology.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Books which
treat of universal principles, of the nature and orders of celestial
beings, of medicine, and other topics.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hermetically</ent>⟦br⟧
